<subSubSection lastPageId="6" lastPageNumber="113" pageId="5" pageNumber="112" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="5.[812,1452,1425,1576]" pageId="5" pageNumber="112">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[812,965,1425,1449]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="112">Description. –</emphasis>
Carapace sparsely setose, legs densely setose. Carapace slightly longer than wide, convex in both directions, with numerous unevenly distributed vesiculous granules. All regions distinct, but not equally well defined. Cervical, branchial and branchio-cardiac grooves well marked.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="5.[812,1452,1617,1832]" pageId="5" pageNumber="112">Rostrum dorsally grooved in mid-line, cut into 3 serrulate teeth, lateral rostral teeth large, triangular, median tooth small and on a lower level. Upper border of orbit serrulate, with a tooth sub-medially. Outer orbital angle pronounced but not dentiform. A straight line connects tip of lateral rostral tooth and postorbital corner, running along anterior carapace margin. Suborbital margin with a granular denticle.</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="5.[812,1451,1873,1960]" pageId="5" pageNumber="112">Anterolateral carapace border cut into 3 blunt granular teeth, the first being subhepatic. Number of teeth variable (see below).</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="5.[812,1451,2001,2088]" lastBlockId="6.[136,775,193,312]" lastPageId="6" lastPageNumber="113" pageId="5" pageNumber="112">Chelipeds more massive than walking legs, these and first pair of walking legs with petaloid meri. Merus of second walking legs not petaloid, although upper border sharp. Inner border of carpus and upper border of propodus prominent, granular, like upper and outer surfaces of these joints; 2 sharp tubercles present on distal end of outer surface of carpus. First 3 pairs of walking legs with few small granules on some joints.</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="6.[136,774,353,504]" pageId="6" pageNumber="113">Last 2 pairs of legs slender, ending in small claw-like dactylus opposable to strong propodal spines. Ratio of length along dorsal margin (not including spine) to width of propodus for third and fourth legs, 1.9 and 1.3, respectively. Last pair of legs slightly longer than penultimate pair.</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="6.[136,775,545,632]" pageId="6" pageNumber="113">
Abdomen in both sexes with central convex ridge, second to fifth tergites with a few scattered granules. (After 
<bibRefCitation author="Alcock, A" pageId="6" pageNumber="113" pagination="123 - 169" refId="ref9538" refString="Alcock, A., 1900. Materials for a Carcinological Fauna of India. No. 5. Brachyura Primigenia or Dromiacea. Journal of the Asiatic Society, Bengal, 1899 (1900), 68 (2): 123 - 169." type="journal article" year="1900">Alcock, 1900</bibRefCitation>
.)
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="6" pageNumber="113" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="6.[136,775,673,920]" pageId="6" pageNumber="113">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[136,259,673,697]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="113">Remarks. –</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Alcock, A" box="[266,435,673,696]" pageId="6" pageNumber="113" pagination="1 - 8" refId="ref9584" refString="Alcock, A., 1901. Catalogue of the Indian Decapod Crustacea in the collection of the Indian Museum. Part I. Brachyura. Fasc. I. Introduction and Dromides or Dromiacea (Brachyura Primigenia). Trustees of the Indian Museum, Calcutta, 80 pp., Pls. 1 - 8." type="book chapter" year="1901">Alcock’s (1901</bibRefCitation>
: Fig 14; present 
<figureCitation box="[610,673,673,696]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="6.[136,170,2065,2086]" captionTargetBox="[138,776,1411,2035]" captionTargetId="figure-8@6.[123,788,1389,2053]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="Fig. 4. Petalomera indica Alcock, 1900:A, overall view; B, posterior view of left first walking leg. (After Alcock, 1900: Fig 14, 14a)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4508061" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4508061/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="113">Fig. 4</figureCitation>
) drawing shows a different number of teeth on the left and right sides for 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Alcock" authorityYear="1900" box="[173,269,737,760]" class="Malacostraca" family="Dromiidae" genus="Petalomera" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="6" pageNumber="113" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="indica">
<emphasis box="[173,269,737,760]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="113">P. indica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. On the left side, there appear to be two distinct teeth followed by one granular lobe, while on the right side, there are no distinct teeth matching those on the left. Behind the cervical groove, his figure shows two granular lobes on the right, but none on the left. Clearly, the arrangement and size of teeth on the anterolateral margins is variable.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="6.[136,775,961,1112]" pageId="6" pageNumber="113">
<bibRefCitation author="Alcock, A" box="[136,290,961,984]" pageId="6" pageNumber="113" pagination="123 - 169" refId="ref9538" refString="Alcock, A., 1900. Materials for a Carcinological Fauna of India. No. 5. Brachyura Primigenia or Dromiacea. Journal of the Asiatic Society, Bengal, 1899 (1900), 68 (2): 123 - 169." type="journal article" year="1900">Alcock (1900)</bibRefCitation>
stated that 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Alcock" authorityYear="1900" box="[411,507,961,984]" class="Malacostraca" family="Dromiidae" genus="Petalomera" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="6" pageNumber="113" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="indica">
<emphasis box="[411,507,961,984]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="113">P. indica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
differed from 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Miers" authorityYear="1884" box="[662,774,961,984]" class="Malacostraca" family="Dromiidae" genus="Petalomera" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="6" pageNumber="113" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pulchra">
<emphasis box="[662,774,961,984]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="113">P. pulchra</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in having a supraorbital tooth and differed from 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Stimpson" authorityYear="1858" box="[641,774,993,1016]" class="Malacostraca" family="Dromiidae" genus="Petalomera" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="6" pageNumber="113" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="granulata">
<emphasis box="[641,774,993,1016]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="113">P. granulata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in not having petaloid meri on the second pair of walking legs. However, it is clear from his fig. 14a (present 
<figureCitation box="[684,767,1057,1080]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="6.[136,170,2065,2086]" captionTargetBox="[138,776,1411,2035]" captionTargetId="figure-8@6.[123,788,1389,2053]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="Fig. 4. Petalomera indica Alcock, 1900:A, overall view; B, posterior view of left first walking leg. (After Alcock, 1900: Fig 14, 14a)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4508061" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4508061/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="113">Fig. 4A</figureCitation>
) that the merus is at least flattened if not petaloid.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="6.[136,775,1153,1240]" pageId="6" pageNumber="113">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[136,204,1153,1177]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="113">Size. –</emphasis>
Maximum size (sex unknown) given by 
<bibRefCitation author="Alcock, A" box="[624,774,1153,1176]" pageId="6" pageNumber="113" pagination="1 - 8" refId="ref9584" refString="Alcock, A., 1901. Catalogue of the Indian Decapod Crustacea in the collection of the Indian Museum. Part I. Brachyura. Fasc. I. Introduction and Dromides or Dromiacea (Brachyura Primigenia). Trustees of the Indian Museum, Calcutta, 80 pp., Pls. 1 - 8." type="book chapter" year="1901">Alcock (1901)</bibRefCitation>
was about 15.0 x 15.0 mm. Smaller specimens have a more elongate carapace than larger specimens.
</paragraph>
